✅ Step-by-Step: Integrate Git into VS Code
🔧 Step 1: Install Git

If Git is not already installed:

Windows:
Download from https://git-scm.com/download/win
 and follow the setup.

macOS:
Run:

brew install git


Linux (Debian/Ubuntu):

sudo apt install git


✅ Verify the installation:

git --version

⚙️ Step 2: Configure Git (First-Time Setup)

Set your Git username and email:

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "you@example.com"

💻 Step 3: Open a Project in VS Code

Launch VS Code

Open a folder (project directory) using:

File > Open Folder


If it’s already a Git repo (has a .git folder), Git will be automatically enabled in VS Code.

🧱 Step 4: Initialize Git (if not already a repo)

If the folder is not yet a Git repository:

Open the Source Control panel (sidebar icon or Ctrl + Shift + G)

Click "Initialize Repository"

Or run:

git init


Now VS Code will show Git options in the Source Control panel.

🔁 Step 5: Use Git Inside VS Code

You can now:

Task	How to do it
Stage changes	Click the + icon next to files
Commit changes	Type a message and click the ✓ icon
Push/pull	Use bottom bar buttons or right-click in Source Control
View branches	Click the branch name in bottom left
Switch branches	Use the same branch menu or Command Palette (Ctrl+Shift+P)
Merge / Rebase	Use terminal or Command Palette
🌐 Step 6: Connect to GitHub (Optional but Useful)
📌 Clone a GitHub Repo

Open Command Palette (Ctrl+Shift+P)

Run:

Git: Clone


Paste the GitHub repo URL

Select folder to save the project

VS Code will prompt to open it

🔐 Set Up GitHub Authentication

When pushing for the first time:

VS Code will prompt for GitHub authentication

Sign in via browser or token

It will remember your credentials (if Git Credential Manager is enabled)

🚀 Bonus: Use Git from VS Code Terminal

Open integrated terminal:

Ctrl + `


You can run any Git commands like:

git status
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git push origin main

🌟 Optional: Install GitLens for Pro Git Tools

GitLens adds:

Line-by-line blame

Visual history

Merge conflict help

File history sidebar

Install it from Extensions view:
Search for GitLens → Click Install

✅ Summary
What You Need	Status
Install Git	✅
Configure Git	✅
Open or init repo in VS Code	✅
Use Git from GUI or terminal	✅
(Optional) Connect to GitHub	✅
(Optional) Install GitLens	✅



